author.value: Collection processed by Yookyung Kwon (March-July 2003), Leif Sorensen (July-September 2004), Melanie Meyers-Cushman (December 2004)

creation.value: This finding aid was produced using ArchivesSpace <date>2018-10-15T21:49:57</date>

abstract.value: Writer and visual artist Michele Zackheim is the author of two novels: <emph render="italic">Violette's Embrace</emph> and <emph render="italic">Einstein's Daughter: the Search for Lieserl</emph>. The Michele Zackheim Papers comprise research materials for the novels, including correspondence, manuscripts, legal documents, publicity material, photographs, books such as biographies and tourist guides, and audio and video cassettes.

p.value: Identification of item, date (if known); Michele Zackheim Papers; MSS 108; box number; folder number; Fales Library and Special Collections, New York University Libraries.

The Michele Zackheim Papers were donated to the Fales Library on December 18, 2000 by Michele Zackheim. An accretion was donated by Michele Zackheim in May of 2018; the accession number associated with the accretion is 2018.084.

Writer and visual artist, Michele Zackheim is the author of two novels. <emph render="italic">Violette's Embrace: A Novel</emph> (Riverhead Books, 1996), is a fictional biography of the French writer Violette Leduc. Her second novel, <emph render="italic">Einstein's Daughter: The Search for Lieserl</emph> (Penguin Putnam, 1999), follows the mystery of the lost illegitimate daughter of Mileva and Albert Einstein. Zackheim has also worked in the visual arts as a fresco muralist, an installation artist, and a painter. She has received two NEA awards, and has taught at the School of Visual Arts in New York City.

The Michele Zackheim Papers are comprised of research material, correspondence, manuscripts, legal documents, publicity material, photographs, audio and video cassettes. The research materials include a copy of August Forel's "Die Frage Sexuelle" with manuscript annotations by Mileva Maric, which was unearthed during one of Zackheim's visits to Serbia. Also included are research materials from various archival collections and duplicates of many of the legal documents related to Evelyn Einstein's lawsuit against the Einstein Family Correspondence Trust. The collection also contains source materials such as books including biographies, auction catalogs, and tours guides that focus on the life of Albert Einstein that were used to help write Zackheim's second novel, <emph render="italic">Einstein's Daughter: The Search for Lieserl</emph>, a biography of Einstein's illegitimate daughter.

Expenses31142042240112undatedoffsite1C17Invoices31142042240112undatedoffsite1C18Series III: EinsteinScope and Contents note

Contains materials related to the production of Zackheim's second novel, Einstein's Daughter: The Search for Lieserl, a biography of Einstein's illegitimate daughter, conceived out of wedlock when Einstein and Mileva Maric were students at Zurich Polytechnic Institute. These files were collected over the five year period in which Zackheim investigated the possible fates of Lieserl. Organized into nine subseries.

Subseries A: ResearchScope and Contents note

Contains Michele Zackheim's research files that include notes, correspondence, books such as biographies and tourist guides, and photographs for Einstein's Daughter. The subseries is arranged alphabetically by author when relevant and subject with the exception of Michele Zackheim's note card file and research binders, which can be found at the end of the subseries. Research Binder # 4 consisting of negatives, contact sheets, and photographs was removed and transferred to subseries G, box 11.
